SIMPLE: synclinal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Synclinal
<hw>Syn*cli"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ to
incline together; <grk>sy`n</grk> with + <?/ to incline.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclined downward from opposite directions, so as to
meet in a common point or line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Formed by strata dipping toward a
common line or plane; <as>as, a <ex>synclinal</ex> trough or valley; a
<ex>synclinal</ex> fold; -- opposed to
<ex>anticlinal</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A downward flexure in the case of folded rocks makes a
<xex>synclinal</xex> axis, and the alternating upward flexure an
<xex>anticlinal</xex> axis.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Synclinal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Synclinal
<hw>Syn*cli"nal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A synclinal
fold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Syncline</ent>⟦br⟧
